# Fluff Date: 2026-02-27 18:01:45
<overview>
<p>Space habitats serve as the residential and administrative anchors of orbital industrial complexes, providing long-term crew accommodations and support facilities for the personnel working aboard nearby factory stations and shipyards. Ranging from compact platforms housing several thousand residents to massive cylinders capable of sheltering populations numbering in the tens of thousands, habitat stations form an essential but often overlooked component of orbital infrastructure. Designed to house the workers, administrators, and technical specialists that keep orbital industry functional, habitats prioritize comfortable, gravity-enabled living spaces through large grav decks, ample cargo space for consumables, and sufficient small craft capacity for regular supply runs to associated stations. Poorly armed and difficult to defend, habitats depend on their civilian status and the practical disincentive of destroying orbital housing for protection; a calculus that did not always prevent their loss during the Inner Sphere's numerous conflicts.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Habitat stations are defined by their emphasis on human-scale living conditions rather than industrial or military function. Extensive residential quarters supported by large grav decks provide the gravity-assisted environment necessary for extended habitation without the health complications of prolonged microgravity exposure. Small craft bays allow for regular crew rotations, supply deliveries, and administrative transport between the habitat and associated orbital facilities. Cargo capacity is oriented toward consumables, medical supplies, and the logistical requirements of a large resident population rather than industrial throughput.</p><p>Defensive armament on larger habitat designs consists of minimal anti-fighter batteries - enough to discourage opportunistic attack but not capable of sustained defense against military forces. Smaller habitat designs carry no weapons at all, relying entirely on their civilian designation for protection. Life support systems and life boat complement are sized for the total residential population, which for larger designs can number in the tens of thousands. The accommodation capacity of large habitat stations (achieved through extensive first-class residential quarters) far exceeds the station's nominal passenger count, reflecting the permanent rather than transient nature of most residents.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Habitat Large (2500) is the most substantial residential orbital platform in widespread deployment, massing 500,000 tons and providing accommodation for populations numbering in the tens of thousands through three large grav decks and extensive residential quarters. Forty small craft bays support the logistics requirements of a population at this scale, and a minimal laser battery provides token anti-fighter defense. Originally constructed to support the labor requirements of major Star League-era industrial or naval complexes, surviving examples represent some of the largest inhabited structures in the Inner Sphere. The Gulf Breeze installation in the Lyran Alliance, formerly C.M.O. 26, is the best-known surviving example of this class.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Space habitats emerged as a byproduct of orbital industrialization, built to address the practical problem of housing large populations near facilities that could not be located on planetary surfaces. The earliest purpose-built residential orbital stations appeared during the Terran Alliance era, but it was during the Star League that habitat construction was most actively pursued, as the growth of orbital factories and shipyards created sustained demand for permanent orbital housing. The Star League's investment in orbital infrastructure extended to substantial habitat construction programs, many supporting the labor requirements of facilities manufacturing equipment for the SLDF and the broader industrial economy.</p><p>The Succession Wars were not immediately catastrophic for habitats in the way they were for factory stations. The civilian nature of habitats and the practical difficulty of causing mass casualties among a non-combatant population without political consequences provided some protection, and early Succession War belligerents frequently preferred to capture functioning habitats rather than destroy them. However, the accumulated damage of decades of conflict, the loss of technical knowledge needed to maintain aging systems, and the economic strain of sustaining stations with declining revenue took a heavy toll. The largest habitats that had been constructed during the Star League era proved especially vulnerable, the great O'Neil cylindrical stations, which had once housed more than a million people each, were destroyed in the wars or rendered non-functional, their loss never offset by replacement construction. By the late twenty-eighth century, most surviving habitats operated at reduced capacity with deteriorating equipment.</p><p>The Fourth Succession War and the broader economic recovery it catalyzed marked a turning point for orbital habitat infrastructure. As orbital factories and shipyards expanded, demand for nearby housing for technical workers grew again, leading to new construction of smaller habitat stations and the refurbishment of surviving older designs. The Gulf Breeze facility in the Lyran Alliance (formerly designated C.M.O. 26) became the best-known surviving example of a large Star League-era habitat, housing some 50,000 military and civilian personnel and representing the largest known constructed habitat remaining in the Inner Sphere. Larger examples are known to exist in Clan space, some holding in excess of 200,000 people, but detailed information on these structures is limited.</p>
</history>

